Pansharpening is a method for enhancing resolution in multispectral images by exploiting the matching spectral signatures of adjacent multispectral bands to synthesize a panchromatic band. In atmospheric science, where the Advanced Baseline Imager (ABI) and the Multi-Spectral Imager are deployed, pansharpening is performed via pixel averaging, meaning that darkened pixels are filled in or brightened pixels are subdued. Unlike filters, which often physically separate different colored bands on a sensor, the adjacent wavelengths of the ABI are spatially within proximity to each other on the focal plane. With pansharpening, you can use the high spatial resolution across and along the swath of the ABI at the cost of significant spectral information loss. The advantage of using pansharpening instead of filtering is that the entire observed feature, from as wide a swath as is collected, is retained. On the other hand, any cost–benefit analysis is usually product specific, and the most suitable preprocessing method is usually determined on a case-by-case basis.
